# Rust Style & Formatting

Let `rustfmt` and `clippy` do the arguing. Treat their output as ground truth.

## Tooling

- Run `rustfmt` on every file before committing — do not fight its decisions
- Run `clippy` with `cargo clippy -- -D warnings`; every warning is a bug
- CI must fail on both `rustfmt --check` and `clippy` warnings
- Use `cargo fix` to apply clippy suggestions automatically when safe

## Naming

| Item | Convention |
|---|---|
| Variables, functions, methods, modules, crates | `snake_case` |
| Types, traits, enums, structs | `PascalCase` |
| Constants, statics | `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` |
| Type parameters | Short `PascalCase` (`T`, `K`, `V`, `E`, `Err`) |
| Lifetimes | Short lowercase `'a`, `'b`; use `'static` only when truly static |
| Macro names | `snake_case!` |

## Layout

- Maximum line length: **100 characters** (rustfmt default)
- One blank line between top-level items
- `use` declarations at the top, grouped: `std` → external crates → crate-local (`crate::`, `super::`, `self::`)
- Avoid deeply nested blocks — extract named functions instead

## Idioms

- Prefer `if let` / `while let` over `match` when only one arm matters
- Use `?` for error propagation — never `.unwrap()` in library code
- Prefer method chaining on iterators over imperative loops
- Avoid `return` at the end of a function — use tail expressions
- Use `_` prefix for intentionally unused variables; never suppress the warning with `#[allow(unused)]` in production code
